    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>An Election Equation: Nader and the X Factor</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jay A Seitz letter says Oct 26 editorial criticizing Ralph Nader's presidential candidacy in effect eviscerates choice in American politics (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your Oct. 26 editorial ''Mr. Nader's Electoral Mischief'' in effect eviscerates choice in American politics. With only two candidates to choose from, should Americans be grateful that the election has boiled down to two seemingly opposing visions of America's future?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your Oct. 26 editorial ''Mr. Nader's Electoral Mischief'' in effect eviscerates choice in American politics. With only two candidates to choose from, should Americans be grateful that the election has boiled down to two seemingly opposing visions of America's future?</p>
        <p>Diversity in national elections should be a hallmark of the electoral process, in which many voices both inside and outside political office contribute to the debate about America's future. By framing this debate and election in ''Al Gore or George W. Bush'' terms, you do a disservice to democracy.</p>
        <p>JAY A. SEITZ  Jamaica, Queens, Oct. 26, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
